What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • The data set contains trip data of users in San Francisco Bay Area with fields as :-
  • There are 183412 observations of the trip in the dataset with 16 columns.
    • Trip Duration(in seconds).
    • Start Time and Date.
    • End Time and Date.
    • Start Station ID.
    • Start Station Name.
    • Start Station Latitude.
    • Start Station Longitude.
    • End Station ID.
    • End Station Name.
    • End Station Latitude.
    • End Station Longitude.
    • Bike ID.
    • User Type (Subscriber or Customer – “Subscriber” = Member or “Customer” = Casual).
    • Member Year of Birth.
    • Member Gender.
    • bike share for all trip.
  • Most variables are numeric in nature, while the variables,start_station_name,end_station_name,member_gender, user_type,bike_share_for_all_trip, are cateogrical in nature.
  • start_time,end_time, are datetime.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • I'm most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting the Duration of the Trip in the dataset.
  • Are there relations between the Trip duration, user type, gender,start station or end station.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • duration_sec.
  • start_station_name.
  • end_station_name.
  • user_type.
  • member_gender.

Data wrangling.¶

Qulity¶

  • Missing Values :-
    • start_station_id : have 197 Null Values.
    • start_station_name : have 197 Null Values.
    • end_station_id : have 197 Null Values.
    • end_station_name : have 197 Null Values.
    • member_birth_year : have 8265 Null Values.
    • member_gender : have 8265 Null Values.
  • start_station_id, end_station_id of float datatype.
  • bike_id of integer datatype.
  • start_time , end_time, are object datatype (str).
  • outliers

Tidiness¶

  • no need for start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude columns.
  • Add a new column for trip duration in minutes.
  • Add a new column for Age.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration takes a large number of values and it is right-skewed, so I looked at it in log transform and found that peak occurs at around 10 minutes, and then distribution starts to dip, with an extreme value up to 1400 minute( the highest trip duration).

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

When performing more analysis on stations where the start station and end station are the same I find that, more skewed observations when the start station is same to end station, with bimodal histogram of trip duration frequency.
